<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-329-092  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 329 092.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  April 9 1990 n265 p54(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber is B.M.O.C. at Case Western. (fiber optics, big man oncampus, Case Western Reserve University)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McPartlin, John P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Case Western Reserve University begins construction of phase twoof its three phase campus-wide fiber optic network.andP;  The 7,000node network costs $12.8 million and, upon its completion in 1991,it will be one of the most advanced fiber optic networks in thecountry.andP;  The network, called CWRUNET, connects faculty buildings,dormitories and the campus library.andP;  Students can access the cardcatalog or retrieve information from CD-ROM devices.andP;  The systemwill link 85 buildings across 128 acres.andP;  Students can use eitheran Apple Macintosh, IBM PC-compatible microcomputer, or Unix-basedmachine with at least 2 Mbytes of memory.andP;  TRW's informationnetworks division is the systems integrator and the University'sinformation systems department manages the network.andP;  Eventually,the IS department would like to add multimedia capabilities to thenetwork to take advantage of fiber optic's high bandwidth.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   TRW Inc. Information Services Div. (services).andO;Topic:     Case Western Reserve UniversityFiber OpticsWide Area NetworksComputer Systems IntegratorsColleges and UniversitiesAutomationNetwork ManagementCommunications Applications.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>